    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Originalism is the legal philosophy that the Constitution should be interpreted based on the original understanding of its text at the time it was ratified. Proponents argue this prevents judges from imposing their personal, subjective policy preferences onto the law. By adhering to original intent or public meaning, originalists ensure the Constitution remains a fixed, stable document rather than a constantly evolving political tool. This approach upholds the separation of powers by keeping policy decisions with the elected branches.",
